Description: HOUSING RIGHTS COMMITTEE is a tenants rights organization that offers free counseling for San Francisco tenants.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: HOUSING RIGHTS COMMITTEE is a tenants rights organization that offers free counseling for San Francisco tenants in all types of housing, including rent-control, SROs, public housing and Section 8. We've been fighting for the rights of tenants since 1979 when a group of seniors at Old St. Mary's Church came together to organize against condo conversions that were displacing the elderly. Housing Rights Committee counselors provide help to over 5,000 tenants a year, advising them on their rights as renters. We offer both call-in and drop-in counseling Monday through Thursday, 1-5pm, 703-8644, 417 South Van Ness/15th. If you come into our office for counseling, you should bring proof of income (check stub, SSI card, food stamp card, benefits award letter, etc.), but no one will be turned away because they don't have it. This does not apply if you call the office for counseling. Our dedicated staff of volunteer counselors are trained to help tenants identify their options when they're having problems with evictions or foreclosure of the place they're living in, illegal rent increases, repair problems, the return of their security deposit, etc.  Housing Rights Committee is a membership organization. Our members make our voice strong and help us continue to support renters in need.

Full Description: Short Term: To connect home care agencies with home health aides or caregivers. Long Term: To connect low paying medical jobs with businesses. Low paying jobs can be defined as that pays less than $20 an hour. These jobs include but are not limited to home health aides, nursing assistants, dietary aides, dental assistants etc. The businesses include hospitals, doctors office, nursing homes, assisted living facilities, independent agencies etc. There are lots of talented people and lots of job sites. But there still is no effective way to connect them. As an employer if you post a job on a website like monster.com, you are inundated with job applications. There is quantity but no heed is given to quality. Companies like LinkedIn are trying to solve this. We believe that there is a better way. If eHarmony could tackle relationships (which are much more complicated) then surely it can be done for jobs too. CrestHire will function in the following way. A) There will be a marketplace that will allow agencies to post jobs. Applicants can apply for these jobs. Agencies can search for applicants and contact them immediately. B) Make the applicant fill an exhaustive questionnaire. The more complete the application is the better the prospects of landing a job. Revenue: It will be a subscription model. The website will start out by providing for a flat fee per month access to X number of caregivers' profile. This will be automatically renewed every month.
